{
    "analysis": "From the previous summary: metric.csv contains 9009 rows across many ts-* services (including ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-travel-service, etc.). trace.csv and log.csv have broad coverage (18584 and 2188 rows respectively). error_logs.csv contains zero raw error entries. Following the prescribed workflow, the next step is metric-based anomaly detection to narrow candidate components and time ranges. We'll compute global thresholds (P95) per component-KPI across the full available series (before any time filtering) and then inspect the incident window (2024-01-24 07:27:12 to 2024-01-24 07:57:12 UTC) for breaches against those global thresholds. This will produce a compact ranked list of component-KPI candidates with earliest breach times and severity metrics to prioritize trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, compute global P95 thresholds per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) over the entire available series (do NOT filter by time before computing P95). Then filter metric.csv to the incident window 2024-01-24 07:27:12 to 2024-01-24 07:57:12 UTC (use pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True) to parse timestamps). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group produce the following compact summary columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points (over full series), p95_value (global P95), window_points (number of rows in the incident window), count_exceed (number of window rows with value > p95_value), earliest_breach_utc (earliest timestamp in window where value > p95_value, or None), max_value_in_window. Return only groups with count_exceed > 0, sorted by count_exceed descending, limit to top 20 rows. Present the result as a JSON-like table/dict with the specified columns." }

{
    "analysis": "From the previous metric scan we found many (cmdb_id, kpi_name) groups breached their global P95 inside the incident window. The breaches are widespread (many services show 1–2 breaches) and include some admin-* services as well as travel and voucher components. The provided possible root-cause components for this task are: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service. We must now narrow to those candidate services and check which of their KPI series show anomalies (count, severity, earliest breach and timestamps) in the incident window so we can use traces/logs next to localize the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, focus on the candidate components: ['ts-auth-service','ts-order-service','ts-route-service','ts-train-service','ts-travel-service']. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global P95 over the full series (do NOT filter by time before computing). Then filter metric data to the incident window 2024-01-24 07:27:12 to 2024-01-24 07:57:12 UTC. For each group produce a compact summary: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points (full series), p95_value, window_points, count_exceed (value > p95_value), breach_timestamps_utc (list of UTC ISO strings of window rows where value > p95_value, limit to first 10), earliest_breach_utc, max_value_in_window, percent_over_p95 = (max_value_in_window - p95_value)/p95_value*100 (if p95_value==0 and max>0 set as Inf). Return only groups with count_exceed > 0, sorted by percent_over_p95 descending then count_exceed desc, limit to top 20. Present result as a JSON/dict table." }
